Independent schools aim to prepare their pupils for further and higher education, their chosen career and their position as world citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a newly created school curriculum, we see that world languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, "If you talk to someone in a language they understand, it goes to their head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it goes to his heart."
It's a powerful reminder that we can't just rely on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year's recent exam scores, we can see that languages are at the top of the league tables with the highest scores in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of pupils who studied foreign languages achieved a higher A.
The data, collected from SCIS' 74 member schools, showed that 72 percent of students achieved a higher degree A in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 of those who studied French and 63 of those who studied Spanish also received an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young adults will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages now, as professional, have the same importance as the STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent schools' curricula and elsewhere.
A survey by the UK Commission on Professions and Skills found in 2014 that of the reasons that employees provide why they struggle to fill jobs, 17 percent are attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for their future careers.
With more likely job opportunities that require languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career one chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future with such a lifelong skill.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically place a multilingual person above the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage, 15 percent.
